# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bevanism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bevanism/100-welsh-heroes] The poll was operated by Culturenet Cymru, a Welsh Assembly-funded body based at the National Library of Wales in Aberystwyth.
[src:bevanism/100-welsh-heroes] At the time of the results being announced the organisers claimed that the 81,323 nominations and votes made it the largest online poll conducted in Wales.
[src:bevanism/100-welsh-heroes] Former Labour leader Neil Kinnock, himself named in the poll, had, during the voting, drawn attention to a Welsh nationalist "plot" to have Owain Glyndŵr at number one, rather than the eventual winner, Aneurin Bevan.
[src:bevanism/100-welsh-heroes] Only nine of the list of a hundred are female, of whom Catherine Zeta-Jones was the most popular, with 1136 votes.
[src:bevanism/100-welsh-heroes] King Arthur, king of the Britons (92 votes) – No.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] The **1955 Labour Party leadership election** was held following the resignation of Clement Attlee.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Attlee was Prime Minister from 1945 to 1951 and stayed on as party leader until he lost the 1955 general election.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Despite his advancing age and Labour's loss of the 1951 general election, Labour Party Leader Clement Attlee delayed his retirement from politics in order to keep the Labour Party united during its fracture between Gaitskellite and Bevanite factions.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] He also did not want Deputy Leader Herbert Morrison to assume full Leadership.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Beginning with the retirement of Hugh Dalton following the 1951 election most senior members of the Labour Party aside from Morrison resigned from the government, leaving the leadership open to a new generation of the party when Attlee finally resigned due to Labour's loss of the 1955 election.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Morrison was once considered the heir apparent to Attlee, but by the early 1950s was widely distrusted and was considered to be too old for the job.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Aneurin Bevan had next been considered the primary front-runner for the Labour Party leadership, but had resigned from the Cabinet in 1951 to protest the introduction of National Health Service prescription charges.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Despite the Bevanites dominating the National Executive Committee, Bevan himself weakened his support through his hostile relations with the Parliamentary Labour Party.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Hugh Gaitskell simultaneously emerged as a potential candidate after a successful tenure as Chancellor of the Exchequer and after the trade union movement which had backed Bevan increasingly gravitated towards him.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Morrison, the leading London politician of his generation, had been an MP since 1923 (with some breaks) and was representing Lewisham South in 1955.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Morrison believed he would easily win against Gaitskell and Bevan on the basis of seniority, despite being warned he would actually be routed due to his old age and unpopularity in the party.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Gaitskell initially endorsed Morrison but entered the race himself in order to prevent Bevan from winning.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Bevan likewise continued his campaign despite being aware he could not win solely to deny Gaitskell the leadership, at one point proposing that they both stand down and allow Morrison to run unopposed.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Gaitskell won the largest victory of any Labour Party leadership election until Neil Kinnock in 1983.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Following the election, Morrison resigned as Deputy Leader of the Labour Party.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Bevan also ran for the subsequent 1956 Labour Party deputy leadership election but narrowly lost to Jim Griffiths.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] However, he performed well enough in the election to be re-elected to Gaitskell's Shadow Cabinet, and the Gaitskellite and Bevanite factions of the party would increasingly reconcile after the Suez Crisis.
[src:bevanism/1955-labour-party-leadership-election] Bevan finally became Deputy Leader after Griffiths' retirement in 1959 and held the office until his death a year later.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] The **1961 Labour Party leadership election** was held when, for the second year in succession, the incumbent leader was challenged for re-election.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] Normally the annual re-election of the leader had been a formality.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] The challenge followed factional in-fighting over issues like nuclear disarmament.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] The leader favoured the retention of nuclear weapons by the UK, whereas the left wing of the party supported the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] The incumbent right-wing leader of the party was Hugh Gaitskell (1906–1963), who had been Chancellor of the Exchequer in 1950–51.
[src:bevanism/1961-labour-party-leadership-election] Gaitskell had been MP for Leeds South since 1945 and party leader since 1955.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The **Age of Enlightenment**, also known as the **Age of Reason** or simply **the Enlightenment**, was a period of intellectual and cultural flourishing in Europe and Western civilization, emerging in the late 17th century in Western Europe.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It reached its peak in the 18th century as its ideas spread more widely across Europe and into the European colonies in the Americas and Oceania.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Characterized by an emphasis on reason, empirical evidence, and the scientific method, the Enlightenment promoted ideals of individual liberty, religious tolerance, progress, and natural rights.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Its thinkers advocated for constitutional government, the separation of church and state, and the application of rational principles to social and political reform.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment emerged from and built upon the Scientific Revolution of the 16th and 17th centuries, which had established new methods of empirical inquiry through the work of figures such as Galileo Galilei, Johannes Kepler, Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, Christiaan Huygens, and Isaac Newton.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Philosophical foundations were laid by thinkers including René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, and John Locke, whose ideas about reason, natural rights, and empirical knowledge became central to Enlightenment thought.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Others cite the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687) as the culmination of the Scientific Revolution and the beginning of the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European historians traditionally dated its beginning with the death of Louis XIV of France in 1715 and its end with the outbreak of the French Revolution in 1789.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many historians now date the end of the Enlightenment as the start of the 19th century, with the latest proposed year being the death of Immanuel Kant in 1804.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The movement was characterized by the widespread circulation of ideas through new institutions: scientific academies, literary salons, coffeehouses, Masonic lodges, and an expanding print culture of books, journals, and pamphlets.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The ideas of the Enlightenment undermined the authority of the monarchy and religious officials and paved the way for the political revolutions of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A variety of 19th-century movements, including liberalism, socialism, and neoclassicism, trace their intellectual heritage to the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] By contrast, other intellectual currents included arguments in favour of anti-Christianity, Deism and Atheism, accompanied by demands for secular states, bans on religious education, suppression of monasteries, the suppression of the Jesuits, and the expulsion of religious orders.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment also faced contemporary criticism, later termed the "Counter-Enlightenment" by Sir Isaiah Berlin, which defended traditional religious and political authorities against rationalist critique.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment was preceded by and closely associated with the Scientific Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Earlier philosophers whose work influenced the Enlightenment included Francis Bacon, Pierre Gassendi, René Descartes, Thomas Hobbes, Baruch Spinoza, John Locke, Pierre Bayle, and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some of the figures of the Enlightenment included Cesare Beccaria, George Berkeley, Denis Diderot, David Hume, Immanuel Kant, Lord Monboddo, Montesquieu, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Adam Smith, Roger Williams, Hugo Grotius, and Voltaire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] One of the most influential Enlightenment publications was the **Encyclopédie** (*Encyclopedia*).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Published between 1751 and 1772 in 35 volumes, it was compiled by Diderot, Jean le Rond d'Alembert, and a team of 150 others.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The *Encyclopédie* helped spread the ideas of the Enlightenment across Europe and beyond.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bacon's empiricism and Descartes' rationalist philosophy laid the foundation for enlightenment thinking.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' attempt to construct the sciences on a secure metaphysical foundation was not as successful as his method of doubt applied to philosophy, which led to a dualistic doctrine of mind and matter.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His skepticism was refined by Locke's *Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1690) and Hume's writings in the 1740s.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Descartes' dualism was challenged by Spinoza's uncompromising assertion of the unity of matter in his *Tractatus* (1670) and *Ethics* (1677).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The moderate variety tended to be deistic whereas the radical tendency separated the basis of morality entirely from theology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both lines of thought were eventually opposed by a conservative Counter-Enlightenment which sought a return to faith.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the mid-18th century, Paris became the center of philosophic and scientific activity challenging traditional doctrines and dogmas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] After the Edict of Fontainebleau in 1685, the relationship between church and the absolutist government was very strong.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The early enlightenment emerged in protest to these circumstances, gaining ground under the support of Madame de Pompadour, the mistress of Louis XV.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Called the *Siècle des Lumières,* the philosophical movement of the Enlightenment had already started by the early 18th century, when Pierre Bayle launched the popular and scholarly Enlightenment critique of religion.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As a skeptic Bayle only partially accepted the philosophy and principles of rationality.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He did draw a strict boundary between morality and religion.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The political philosopher Montesquieu introduced the idea of a separation of powers in a government, a concept which was enthusiastically adopted by the authors of the United States Constitution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the *philosophes* of the French Enlightenment were not revolutionaries and many were members of the nobility, their ideas played an important part in undermining the legitimacy of the Old Regime and shaping the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume became a major figure in the skeptical philosophical and empiricist traditions of philosophy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom and political authority, as well as map out a view of the public sphere through private and public reason.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Kant's work continued to influence German intellectual life and European philosophy more broadly well into the 20th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Mary Wollstonecraft was one of England's earliest feminist philosophers.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She argued for a society based on reason and that women as well as men should be treated as rational beings.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] She is best known for her 1792 work, *A Vindication of the Rights of Woman*.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science played an important role in Enlightenment discourse and thought.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many Enlightenment writers and thinkers had backgrounds in the sciences and associated scientific advancement with the overthrow of religion and traditional authority in favour of the development of free speech and thought.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The experiments of Antoine Lavoisier were used to create the first modern chemical plants in Paris, and the experiments of the Montgolfier brothers enabled them to launch the first manned flight in a hot air balloon in 1783.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Broadly speaking, Enlightenment science greatly valued empiricism and rational thought and was embedded with the Enlightenment ideal of advancement and progress.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The study of science, under the heading of natural philosophy, was divided into physics and a conglomerate grouping of chemistry and natural history, which included anatomy, biology, geology, mineralogy, and zoology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As with most Enlightenment views, the benefits of science were not seen universally: Rousseau criticized the sciences for distancing man from nature and not operating to make people happier.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Science during the Enlightenment was dominated by scientific societies and academies, which had largely replaced universities as centres of scientific research and development.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Societies and academies were also the backbone of the maturation of the scientific profession.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Scientific academies and societies grew out of the Scientific Revolution as the creators of scientific knowledge, in contrast to the scholasticism of the university.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some societies created or retained links to universities, but contemporary sources distinguished universities from scientific societies by claiming that the university's utility was in the transmission of knowledge while societies functioned to create knowledge.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] As the role of universities in institutionalized science began to diminish, learned societies became the cornerstone of organized science.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Official scientific societies were chartered by the state to provide technical expertise.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Most societies were granted permission to oversee their own publications, control the election of new members and the administration of the society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the 18th century, a very large number of official academies and societies were founded in Europe; by 1789 there were over 70 official scientific societies.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In reference to this growth, Bernard de Fontenelle coined the term "the Age of Academies" to describe the 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Another important development was the popularization of science among an increasingly literate population.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] *Philosophes* introduced the public to many scientific theories, most notably through the *Encyclopédie* and the popularization of Newtonianism by Voltaire and Émilie du Châtelet.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some historians have marked the 18th century as a drab period in the history of science.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The century saw significant advancements in the practice of medicine, mathematics, and physics; the development of biological taxonomy; a new understanding of magnetism and electricity; and the maturation of chemistry as a discipline, which established the foundations of modern chemistry.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The influence of science began appearing more commonly in poetry and literature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While some societies were established with ties to universities or maintained existing ones contemporary sources often distinguished between the two, asserting that universities primarily served to transmit knowledge, whereas scientific societies were oriented toward the creation of new knowledge.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] James Thomson penned his "A Poem to the Memory of Sir Isaac Newton," which mourned the loss of Newton and praised his science and legacy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Modern sociology largely originated from this movement, and Hume's philosophical concepts that directly influenced James Madison (and thus the U.S.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution), and as popularised by Dugald Stewart was the basis of classical liberalism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In 1776, Adam Smith published *The Wealth of Nations,* often considered the first work on modern economics as it had an immediate impact on British economic policy that continues into the 21st century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It was immediately preceded and influenced by Anne Robert Jacques Turgot's drafts of *Reflections on the Formation and Distribution of Wealth* (1766).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Smith acknowledged indebtedness and possibly was the original English translator.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Beccaria, a jurist, criminologist, philosopher, and politician and one of the great Enlightenment writers, became famous for his masterpiece *Dei delitti e delle pene* (Of Crimes and Punishments, 1764).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] His treatise, translated into 22 languages, condemned torture and the death penalty and was a founding work in the field of penology and the classical school of criminology by promoting criminal justice.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Francesco Mario Pagano wrote studies such as *Saggi politici* (Political Essays, 1783); and *Considerazioni sul processo criminale* (Considerations on the Criminal Trial, 1787), which established him as an international authority on criminal law.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has long been seen as the foundation of modern Western political and intellectual culture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment brought political modernization to the West, in terms of introducing democratic values and institutions and the creation of modern, liberal democracies.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This thesis has been widely accepted by scholars and has been reinforced by the large-scale studies by Robert Darnton, Roy Porter, and, most recently, by Jonathan Israel.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment thought was deeply influential in the political realm.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] European rulers such as Catherine II of Russia, Joseph II of Austria, and Frederick II of Prussia tried to apply Enlightenment thought on religious and political tolerance, which became known as enlightened absolutism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Constitution during its framing in 1787.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, based his governance philosophy on social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] English philosopher Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work *Leviathan* in 1651.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Locke and Rousseau developed social contract theories in *Two Treatises of Government* and *Discourse on Inequality*, respectively.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While quite different works, Locke, Hobbes, and Rousseau agreed that a social contract, in which the government's authority lies in the consent of the governed, is necessary for man to live in civil society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke defines the state of nature as a condition in which humans are rational and follow natural law, in which all men are born equal and with the right to life, liberty, and property.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] However, when one citizen breaks the law of nature both the transgressor and the victim enter into a state of war, from which it is virtually impossible to break free.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore, Locke said that individuals enter into civil society to protect their natural rights via an "unbiased judge" or common authority, such as courts.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In contrast, Rousseau's conception relies on the supposition that "civil man" is corrupted, while "natural man" has no want he cannot fulfill himself.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Natural man is only taken out of the state of nature when the inequality associated with private property is established.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rousseau said that people join into civil society via the social contract to achieve unity while preserving individual freedom.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] This is embodied in the sovereignty of the general will, the moral and collective legislative body constituted by citizens.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke is known for his statement that individuals have a right to "Life, Liberty, and Property," and his belief that the natural right to property is derived from labor.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Declaration of Independence and the French National Constituent Assembly's Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Some *philosophes* argued that the establishment of a contractual basis of rights would lead to the market mechanism and capitalism, the scientific method, religious tolerance, and the organization of states into self-governing republics through democratic means.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In this view, the tendency of the *philosophes* in particular to apply rationality to every problem is considered the essential change.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Although much of Enlightenment political thought was dominated by social contract theorists, Hume and Ferguson criticized this camp.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Hume's essay *Of the Original Contract* argues that governments derived from consent are rarely seen and civil government is grounded in a ruler's habitual authority and force.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] It is precisely because of the ruler's authority over-and-against the subject that the subject tacitly consents, and Hume says that the subjects would "never imagine that their consent made him sovereign," rather the authority did so.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Similarly, Ferguson did not believe citizens built the state, rather polities grew out of social development.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In his 1767 *An Essay on the History of Civil Society,* Ferguson uses the four stages of progress, a theory that was popular in Scotland at the time, to explain how humans advance from a hunting and gathering society to a commercial and civil society without agreeing to a social contract.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Both Rousseau's and Locke's social contract theories rest on the presupposition of natural rights, which are not a result of law or custom but are things that all men have in pre-political societies and are therefore universal and inalienable.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The most famous natural right formulation comes from Locke's *Second Treatise,* when he introduces the state of nature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, the law of nature is grounded on mutual security or the idea that one cannot infringe on another's natural rights, as every man is equal and has the same inalienable rights.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These natural rights include perfect equality and freedom, as well as the right to preserve life and property.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues against indentured servitude on the basis that enslaving oneself goes against the law of nature because a person cannot surrender their own rights: freedom is absolute, and no one can take it away.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke argues that one person cannot enslave another because it is morally reprehensible, although he introduces a caveat by saying that enslavement of a lawful captive in time of war would not go against one's natural rights.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The leaders of the Enlightenment were not especially democratic, as they more often look to absolute monarchs as the key to imposing reforms designed by the intellectuals.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In several nations, rulers welcomed leaders of the Enlightenment at court and asked them to help design laws and programs to reform the system, typically to build stronger states.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These rulers are called "enlightened despots" by historians.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They included Frederick the Great of Prussia, Catherine the Great of Russia, Leopold II of Tuscany and Joseph II of Austria.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Joseph was over-enthusiastic, announcing many reforms that had little support so that revolts broke out and his regime became a comedy of errors, and nearly all his programs were reversed.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Senior ministers Pombal in Portugal and Johann Friedrich Struensee in Denmark also governed according to Enlightenment ideals.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In Poland, the model constitution of 1791 expressed Enlightenment ideals, but was in effect for only one year before the nation was partitioned among its neighbors.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] More enduring were the cultural achievements, which created a nationalist spirit in Poland.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Frederick the Great, the king of Prussia from 1740 to 1786, saw himself as a leader of the Enlightenment and patronized philosophers and scientists at his court in Berlin.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Voltaire, who had been imprisoned and maltreated by the French government, was eager to accept Frederick's invitation to live at his palace.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The Enlightenment has been frequently linked to the American Revolution of 1776 and the French Revolution of 1789—both had some intellectual influence from Thomas Jefferson.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] A key aspect of this era was a profound shift from the absolute monarchies of Europe, which asserted the "divine right" to rule.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] John Locke rejected this view in his writings on the Two Treatises of Government (1689).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He asserted that citizens were seen to possess natural rights, including life, liberty, and property.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Therefore governments exist to protect these rights through the "consent of the governed." The clash between these competing ethos often resulted in violent upheaval in differing ways.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In France, Ancien régime, with its rigid social hierarchy and absolute monarchical power, was systematically dismantled during the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] While the American Revolution focused more on breaking free from a government - represented by King George III and Parliament - that colonists felt did not adequately represent their interests.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Alexis de Tocqueville proposed the French Revolution as the inevitable result of the radical opposition created in the 18th century between the monarchy and the men of letters of the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These men of letters constituted a sort of "substitute aristocracy that was both all-powerful and without real power." This illusory power came from the rise of "public opinion," born when absolutist centralization removed the nobility and the bourgeoisie from the political sphere.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "literary politics" that resulted promoted a discourse of equality and was hence in fundamental opposition to the monarchical regime.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment era religious commentary was a response to the preceding century of religious conflict in Europe, especially the Thirty Years' War.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Theologians of the Enlightenment wanted to reform their faith to its generally non-confrontational roots and to limit the capacity for religious controversy to spill over into politics and warfare while still maintaining a true faith in God.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For moderate Christians, this meant a return to simple Scripture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke abandoned the corpus of theological commentary in favor of an "unprejudiced examination" of the Word of God alone.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He determined the essence of Christianity to be a belief in Christ the redeemer and recommended avoiding more detailed debate.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In the *Jefferson Bible,* Thomas Jefferson went further and dropped any passages dealing with miracles, visitations of angels, and the resurrection of Jesus after his death, as he tried to extract the practical Christian moral code of the New Testament.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Enlightenment scholars sought to curtail the political power of organized religion and thereby prevent another age of intolerant religious war.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Spinoza determined to remove politics from contemporary and historical theology (e.g., disregarding Judaic law).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Moses Mendelssohn advised affording no political weight to any organized religion but instead recommended that each person follow what they found most convincing.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] They believed a good religion based in instinctive morals and a belief in God should not theoretically need force to maintain order in its believers, and both Mendelssohn and Spinoza judged religion on its moral fruits, not the logic of its theology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Several novel ideas about religion developed with the Enlightenment, including deism and talk of atheism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to Thomas Paine, deism is the simple belief in God the Creator with no reference to the Bible or any other miraculous source.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Instead, the deist relies solely on personal reason to guide his creed, which was eminently agreeable to many thinkers of the time.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Atheism was much discussed, but there were few proponents.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Wilson and Reill note: "In fact, very few enlightened intellectuals, even when they were vocal critics of Christianity, were true atheists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Rather, they were critics of orthodox belief, wedded rather to skepticism, deism, vitalism, or perhaps pantheism." Some followed Pierre Bayle and argued that atheists could indeed be moral men.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Many others like Voltaire held that without belief in a God who punishes evil, the moral order of society was undermined; that is, since atheists gave themselves to no supreme authority and no law and had no fear of eternal consequences, they were far more likely to disrupt society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Bayle observed that, in his day, "prudent persons will always maintain an appearance of [religion]," and he believed that even atheists could hold concepts of honor and go beyond their own self-interest to create and interact in society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Locke said that if there were no God and no divine law, the result would be moral anarchy: every individual "could have no law but his own will, no end but himself.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] The "Radical Enlightenment" promoted the concept of separating church and state, an idea that is often credited to Locke.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] According to his principle of the social contract, Locke said that the government lacked authority in the realm of individual conscience, as this was something rational people could not cede to the government for it or others to control.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] For Locke, this created a natural right in the liberty of conscience, which he said must therefore remain protected from any government authority.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] These views on religious tolerance and the importance of individual conscience, along with the social contract, became particularly influential in the American colonies and the drafting of the United States Constitution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] In a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association in Connecticut, Thomas Jefferson calls for a "wall of separation between church and state" at the federal level.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] He previously had supported successful efforts to disestablish the Church of England in Virginia and authored the Virginia Statute for Religious Freedom.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p01] Jefferson's political ideals were greatly influenced by the writings of Locke, Bacon, and Newton, whom he considered the three greatest men that ever lived.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment took hold in most European countries and influenced nations globally, often with a specific local emphasis.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] For example, in France it became associated with anti-government and anti-Church radicalism, while in Germany it reached deep into the middle classes, where it expressed a spiritualistic and nationalistic tone without threatening governments or established churches.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, the government was hostile, and the *philosophes* fought against its censorship, sometimes being imprisoned or hounded into exile.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The British government, for the most part, ignored the Enlightenment's leaders in England and Scotland, although it did give Newton a knighthood and a very lucrative government office.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A common theme among most countries which derived Enlightenment ideas from Europe was the intentional non-inclusion of Enlightenment philosophies pertaining to slavery.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1791, the Haitian Revolution, a slave rebellion by emancipated slaves against French colonial rule in the colony of Saint-Domingue, broke out.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The very existence of an English Enlightenment has been hotly debated by scholars.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The majority of textbooks on British history make little or no mention of an English Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Some surveys of the entire Enlightenment include England and others ignore it, although they do include coverage of such major intellectuals as Joseph Addison, Edward Gibbon, John Locke, Isaac Newton, Alexander Pope, Joshua Reynolds, and Jonathan Swift.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freethinking, a term describing those who stood in opposition to the institution of the Church, and the literal belief in the Bible, can be said to have begun in England no later than 1713, when Anthony Collins wrote his "Discourse of Free-thinking," which gained substantial popularity.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This essay attacked the clergy of all churches and was a plea for deism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Roy Porter argues that the reasons for this neglect were the assumptions that the movement was primarily French-inspired, that it was largely a-religious or anti-clerical, and that it stood in outspoken defiance to the established order.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter admits that after the 1720s England could claim thinkers to equal Diderot, Voltaire, or Rousseau.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, its leading intellectuals such as Gibbon, Edmund Burke and Samuel Johnson were all quite conservative and supportive of the standing order.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Porter says the reason was that Enlightenment had come early to England and had succeeded such that the culture had accepted political liberalism, philosophical empiricism, and religious toleration, positions which intellectuals on the continent had to fight against powerful odds.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Furthermore, England rejected the collectivism of the continent and emphasized the improvement of individuals as the main goal of enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Derek Hirst, the 1640s and 1650s saw a revived economy characterised by growth in manufacturing, the elaboration of financial and credit instruments, and the commercialisation of communication.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The gentry found time for leisure activities, such as horse racing and bowling.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the high culture important innovations included the development of a mass market for music, increased scientific research, and an expansion of publishing.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] All the trends were discussed in depth at the newly established coffee houses.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the Scottish Enlightenment, the principles of sociability, equality, and utility were disseminated in schools and universities, many of which used sophisticated teaching methods which blended philosophy with daily life.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scotland's major cities created an intellectual infrastructure of mutually supporting institutions such as schools, universities, reading societies, libraries, periodicals, museums, and Masonic lodges.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Several Americans, especially Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson, played a major role in bringing Enlightenment ideas to the New World and in influencing British and French thinkers.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin was influential for his political activism and for his advances in physics.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Franklin also broadly encouraged the individual's rights and responsibilities to serve as an educated and informed citizen.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He published yearly the widely popular, *Poor Richard's Almanack,* filled with witty quotes encouraging disciplined self-learning, such as "Early to bed, early to rise, makes a man healthy, wealthy and wise." The cultural exchange during the Enlightenment ran in both directions across the Atlantic.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Thinkers such as Paine, Locke, and Rousseau all take Native American cultural practices as examples of natural freedom.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Americans closely followed English and Scottish political ideas, as well as some French thinkers such as Montesquieu.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] As deists, they were influenced by ideas of John Toland and Matthew Tindal.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was a great emphasis upon liberty, republicanism, and religious tolerance.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There was no respect for monarchy or inherited political power.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Deists reconciled science and religion by rejecting prophecies, miracles, and biblical theology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leading deists included Thomas Paine in *The Age of Reason* and Thomas Jefferson in his short *Jefferson Bible,* from which he removed all supernatural aspects.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Jewish Enlightenment, or *Haskalah* (Hebrew: הַשְׂכָּלָה, "education") was an intellectual movement among the Jews of Central and Eastern Europe, with a certain influence on those in Western Europe and the Muslim world.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It arose as a defined ideological worldview during the 1770s, and its last stage ended around 1881, with the rise of Jewish nationalism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement advocated against Jewish reclusiveness, encouraged the adoption of prevalent attire over traditional dress, while also working to diminish the authority of traditional community institutions such as rabbinic courts and boards of elders.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Early Dutch Enlightenment (1640–1720), many books were translated from Latin, French or English to Dutch, often at the risk of their translators and publishers.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the 1720s, the Dutch Republic had also become a major center for printing and exporting banned books to France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Implanted in Netherlandish culture, vernacular rationalism brought the Dutch to take advantage of the intellectual philosophy the enlightenment spread.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The most famous figure of the Dutch Enlightenment was Baruch Spinoza.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The French Enlightenment was influenced by England and in turn influenced other national enlightenments.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Prussia took the lead among the German states in sponsoring the political reforms that Enlightenment thinkers urged absolute rulers to adopt.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There were important movements as well in the smaller states of Bavaria, Saxony, Hanover, and the Palatinate.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In each case, Enlightenment values became accepted and led to significant political and administrative reforms that laid the groundwork for the creation of modern states.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The princes of Saxony, for example, carried out an impressive series of fundamental fiscal, administrative, judicial, educational, cultural, and general economic reforms.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reforms were aided by the country's strong urban structure and influential commercial groups and modernized pre-1789 Saxony along the lines of classic Enlightenment principles.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Before 1750, the German upper classes looked to France for intellectual, cultural, and architectural leadership, as French was the language of high society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By the mid-18th century, the *Aufklärung* (The Enlightenment) had transformed German high culture in music, philosophy, science, and literature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Christian Wolff was the pioneer as a writer who expounded the Enlightenment to German readers and legitimized German as a philosophic language.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Johann Gottfried von Herder broke new ground in philosophy and poetry, as a leader of the Sturm und Drang movement of proto-Romanticism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Weimar Classicism (*Weimarer Klassik*) was a cultural and literary movement based in Weimar that sought to establish a new humanism by synthesizing Romantic, classical, and Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement (from 1772 until 1805) involved Herder as well as polymath Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller, a poet and historian.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The theatre principal Abel Seyler greatly influenced the development of German theatre and promoted serious German opera, new works and experimental productions, and the concept of a national theatre.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Herder argued that every group of people had its own particular identity, which was expressed in its language and culture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This legitimized the promotion of German language and culture and helped shape the development of German nationalism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Schiller's plays expressed the restless spirit of his generation, depicting the hero's struggle against social pressures and the force of destiny.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German music, sponsored by the upper classes, came of age under composers Johann Sebastian Bach, Joseph Haydn, and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In remote Königsberg, Kant tried to reconcile rationalism and religious belief, individual freedom, and political authority.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Kant's work contained basic tensions that would continue to shape German thought—and indeed all of European philosophy—well into the 20th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German Enlightenment won the support of princes, aristocrats, and the middle classes, and it permanently reshaped the culture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, there was a conservatism among the elites that warned against going too far.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1788, Prussia issued an "Edict on Religion" that forbade preaching any sermon that undermined popular belief in the Holy Trinity or the Bible.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The goal was to avoid theological disputes that might impinge on domestic tranquility.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Men who doubted the value of Enlightenment favoured the measure, but so too did many supporters.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] German universities had created a closed elite that could debate controversial issues among themselves, but spreading them to the public was seen as too risky.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This intellectual elite was favoured by the state, but that might be reversed if the process of the Enlightenment proved politically or socially destabilizing.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, Austria was under Habsburg rule.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The reign of Maria Theresa, the first Habsburg monarch to be considered influenced by the Enlightenment in some areas, was marked by a mix of enlightenment and conservatism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Her son Joseph II's brief reign was marked by this conflict, with his ideology of Josephinism facing opposition.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph II carried out numerous reforms in the spirit of the Enlightenment, which affected, for example, the school system, monasteries and the legal system.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Emperor Leopold II, who was an early opponent of capital punishment, had a brief and contentious rule that was mostly marked by relations with France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Similarly, Emperor Francis II's rule was primarily marked by relations with France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment also appeared in literature and theater works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Joseph von Sonnenfels was an important representative.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In music, Austrian musicians such as Joseph Haydn and Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart were associated with the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Modern Greek Enlightenment (Greek: Διαφωτισμός, Diafotismós) was the Greek expression of the Enlightenment, characterized by an intellectual and philosophical movement within the Greek community.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At this time, many Greeks were dispersed across the Ottoman Empire, with some residing on the Ionian Islands, in Venice, and other parts of Italy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century, while Hungary was part of the Habsburg Empire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Hungarian Enlightenment is usually said to have begun in 1772 and was greatly influenced by French Enlightenment (through Vienna).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Romanian Enlightenment emerged during the 18th century across the three major historical regions inhabited by Romanians: Transylvania, Wallachia, and Moldavia.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] At that time, Transylvania was in the Habsburg Empire while Wallachia and Moldavia were vassals of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Transylvanian Enlightenment was represented by the Transylvanian School, a group of thinkers who promoted a cultural revival and rights for Romanians (who were marginalized by the Habsburgs).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Wallachian Enlightenment was represented by such figures as Dinicu Golescu (1777–1830), while the Moldavian Englightenment was headed by prince Dimitrie Cantemir (1673-1723).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment arrived relatively late in Switzerland, spreading from England, the Netherlands, and France toward the end of the 17th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement initially took hold in Protestant regions, where it gradually replaced orthodox religious thinking.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The 1712 victory of the reformed cantons of Zurich and Bern over the five Catholic cantons of central Switzerland in the Second War of Villmergen marked both a Protestant triumph and a victory for Enlightenment ideas in the economically more developed regions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Switzerland, which lacked a central court or academy, the Enlightenment spread through the intellectual elite of reformed cities, particularly pastors educated in academies and colleges with strong humanist traditions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss Enlightenment thinkers made significant contributions across multiple fields.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, Johann Jakob Bodmer and Johann Jakob Breitinger made Zurich a center of German literary innovation, while Albert von Haller's poetry represented the peak of Swiss Enlightenment literature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean-Jacques Rousseau, considering himself both a Genevan and Swiss citizen, developed democratic republican theories that extended Genevan models to broader European federalist principles.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement was characterized by what scholars term "Helvetism" – specifically Swiss aspects including a Christian conception of natural law, patriotic ethics, and philosophical approaches grounded in practical pedagogy and economics.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most distinctively, Swiss Enlightenment thought celebrated Alpine nature, viewing Switzerland as the "land of shepherds" whose republican and federalist traditions were shaped by its mountain environment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement organized through numerous societies and publications, including the *Encyclopédie d'Yverdon* (1770-1780), which offered a moderate alternative to the French *Encyclopédie*.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Swiss intellectuals gained international prominence, with many serving in foreign academies, particularly in Berlin under Frederick II and in St.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Italy, the main centers of diffusion of the Enlightenment were Naples and Milan: in both cities the intellectuals took public office and collaborated with the Bourbon and Habsburg administrations.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Naples, Antonio Genovesi, Ferdinando Galiani, and Gaetano Filangieri were active under the tolerant King Charles of Bourbon.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, the Neapolitan Enlightenment, like Vico's philosophy, remained almost always in the theoretical field.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Only later, many Enlighteners animated the unfortunate experience of the Parthenopean Republic.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Milan, however, the movement strove to find concrete solutions to problems.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The center of discussions was the magazine *Il Caffè* (1762–1766), founded by brothers Pietro and Alessandro Verri (famous philosophers and writers, as well as their brother Giovanni), who also gave life to the Accademia dei Pugni, founded in 1761.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Minor centers were Tuscany, Veneto, and Piedmont, where among others, Pompeo Neri worked.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Naples, Genovesi influenced a generation of southern Italian intellectuals and university students.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His textbook *Della diceosina, o sia della Filosofia del Giusto e dell'Onesto* (1766) was a controversial attempt to mediate between the history of moral philosophy on the one hand and the specific problems encountered by 18th-century commercial society on the other.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It contained the greater part of Genovesi's political, philosophical, and economic thought, which became a guidebook for Neapolitan economic and social development.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Science flourished as Alessandro Volta and Luigi Galvani made break-through discoveries in electricity.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Pietro Verri was a leading economist in Lombardy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Historian Joseph Schumpeter states he was "the most important pre-Smithian authority on Cheapness-and-Plenty." The most influential scholar on the Italian Enlightenment has been Franco Venturi.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Italy also produced some of the Enlightenment's greatest legal theorists, including Cesare Beccaria, Giambattista Vico, and Francesco Mario Pagano.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Charles II, the last Spanish Habsburg monarch, died his successor was from the French House of Bourbon, initiating a period of French Enlightenment influence in Spain and the Spanish Empire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 18th Century, the Spanish continued to expand their empire in the Americas with the Spanish missions in California and established missions deeper inland in South America.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Under Charles III, the crown began to implement serious structural changes.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The monarchy curtailed the power of the Catholic Church, and established a standing military in Spanish America.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Freer trade was promoted under *comercio libre* in which regions could trade with companies sailing from any other Spanish port, rather than the restrictive mercantile system.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The crown sent out scientific expeditions to assert Spanish sovereignty over territories it claimed but did not control, but also importantly to discover the economic potential of its far-flung empire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Botanical expeditions sought plants that could be of use to the empire.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Charles IV gave Prussian scientist Alexander von Humboldt free rein to travel in Spanish America, usually closed to foreigners, and more importantly, access to crown officials to aid the success of his scientific expedition.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] When Napoleon invaded Spain in 1808, Ferdinand VII abdicated and Napoleon placed his brother Joseph Bonaparte on the throne.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] To add legitimacy to this move, the Bayonne Constitution was promulgated, which included representation from Spain's overseas components, but most Spaniards rejected the whole Napoleonic project.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Cortes de Cádiz (parliament) was convened to rule Spain in the absence of the legitimate monarch, Ferdinand.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The constitution was in effect from 1812 until 1814, when Napoleon was defeated and Ferdinand was restored to the throne of Spain.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Upon his return, Ferdinand repudiated the constitution and reestablished absolutist rule.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Haitian Revolution began in 1791 and ended in 1804 and shows how Enlightenment ideas "were part of complex transcultural flows." Radical ideas in Paris during and after the French Revolution were mobilized in Haiti, such as by Toussaint Louverture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Portuguese Enlightenment was heavily marked by the rule of Prime Minister Marquis of Pombal under King Joseph I from 1756 to 1777.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His urbanistic ideas, also being the first large-scale example of earthquake engineering, became collectively known as Pombaline style, and were implemented throughout the kingdom during his stay in office.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] His governance was as enlightened as ruthless, see for example the Távora affair.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In literature, the first Enlightenment ideas in Portugal can be traced back to the diplomat, philosopher, and writer António Vieira who spent a considerable amount of his life in colonial Brazil denouncing discriminations against New Christians and the indigenous peoples in Brazil.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the 18th century, enlightened literary movements such as the Arcádia Lusitana (lasting from 1756 until 1776, then replaced by the Nova Arcádia in 1790 until 1794) surfaced in the academic medium, in particular involving former students of the University of Coimbra.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A distinct member of this group was the poet Manuel Maria Barbosa du Bocage.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The physician António Nunes Ribeiro Sanches was also an important Enlightenment figure, contributing to the *Encyclopédie* and being part of the Russian court.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The ideas of the Enlightenment influenced various economists and anti-colonial intellectuals throughout the Portuguese Empire, such as José de Azeredo Coutinho, José da Silva Lisboa, Cláudio Manoel da Costa, and Tomás Antônio Gonzaga.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Napoleonic invasion of Portugal had consequences for the Portuguese monarchy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] With the aid of the British navy, the Portuguese royal family was evacuated to Brazil, its most important colony.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Even though Napoleon had been defeated, the royal court remained in Brazil.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Liberal Revolution of 1820 forced the return of the royal family to Portugal.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The terms by which the restored king was to rule was a constitutional monarchy under the Constitution of Portugal.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Brazil declared its independence from Portugal in 1822 and became a monarchy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The existence of a Swedish Enlightenment has been debated by scholars.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Between 1718 and 1772, the Swedish Enlightenment overlapped with the period of parliamentary rule known in Swedish history as the Age of Liberty.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In Russia, the government began to actively encourage the proliferation of arts and sciences in the mid-18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] This era produced the first Russian university, library, theatre, public museum, and independent press.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Like other enlightened despots, Catherine the Great played a key role in fostering the arts, sciences and education.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] She used her own interpretation of Enlightenment ideals, assisted by notable international experts such as Voltaire (by correspondence) and in residence world class scientists such as Leonhard Euler and Peter Simon Pallas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The national Enlightenment differed from its Western European counterpart in that it promoted further modernization of all aspects of Russian life and was concerned with attacking the institution of serfdom in Russia.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Russian Enlightenment centered on the individual instead of societal enlightenment and encouraged the living of an enlightened life.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A powerful element was *prosveshchenie* which combined religious piety, erudition, and commitment to the spread of learning.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, it lacked the skeptical and critical spirit of the Western European Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment ideas (*oświecenie*) emerged late in Poland, as the Polish middle class was weaker and szlachta (nobility) culture (Sarmatism) together with the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth political system (Golden Liberty) were in deep crisis.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The political system was built on aristocratic republicanism, but was unable to defend itself against powerful neighbors Russia, Prussia, and Austria as they repeatedly sliced off regions until nothing was left of independent Poland.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Polish Enlightenment began in the 1730s–40s and especially in theatre and the arts peaked in the reign of King Stanisław August Poniatowski (second half of the 18th century).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Warsaw was a main centre after 1750, with an expansion of schools and educational institutions and the arts patronage held at the Royal Castle.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Leaders promoted tolerance and more education.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] They included King Stanislaw II August and reformers Piotr Switkowski, Antoni Poplawski, Josef Niemcewicz, and Jósef Pawlinkowski, as well as Baudouin de Cortenay, a Polonized dramatist.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Opponents included Florian Jaroszewicz, Gracjan Piotrowski, Karol Wyrwicz, and Wojciech Skarszewski.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The movement went into decline with the Third Partition of Poland (1795) – a national tragedy inspiring a short period of sentimental writing – and ended in 1822, replaced by Romanticism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From 1641 to 1853, the Tokugawa shogunate of Japan enforced a policy called *kaikin.* The policy prohibited foreign contact with most outside countries.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During this time, Korea "aimed at isolation" and was known as the "hermit kingdom" but became awakened to Enlightenment ideas by the 1890s such as with the activities of the Independence Club.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Korea was influenced by China and Japan but also found its own Enlightenment path with the Korean intellectual Yu Kilchun who popularized the term Enlightenment throughout Korea.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 18th-century India, Tipu Sultan was an enlightened monarch, who "was one of the founding members of the (French) Jacobin Club in Seringapatam, had planted a liberty tree, and asked to be addressed as 'Tipu Citoyen,'" which means Citizen Tipu.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In parts of India, an important movement called the "Bengal Renaissance" led to Enlightenment reforms beginning in the 1820s.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Enlightenment began to influence the Ottoman Empire in the 1830s and continued into the late 19th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Tanzimat was a period of reform in the Ottoman Empire that began with the Gülhane Hatt-ı Şerif in 1839 and ended with the First Constitutional Era in 1876.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The Arab Enlightenment, or *Nahda* (Arabic: النّهضة, "the awakening"), was a cultural movement in Arab-populated regions of the Ottoman Empire such as Egypt, Lebanon, Syria, and Tunisia, during the second half of the 19th century and the early 20th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The *Nahda* is often traced to the cultural shock of the French invasion of Egypt and Syria in 1798, and the reformist drive of subsequent rulers such as Muhammad Ali of Egypt.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The idea of the Enlightenment has always been contested territory.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] According to Keith Thomas, its supporters "hail it as the source of everything that is progressive about the modern world.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From the start, conservative and clerical defenders of traditional religion attacked materialism and skepticism as evil forces that encouraged immorality.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] By 1794, they pointed to the Reign of Terror during the French Revolution as confirmation of their predictions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Romantic philosophers argued that the Enlightenment's excessive dependence on reason was a mistake that it perpetuated, disregarding the bonds of history, myth, faith, and tradition that were necessary to hold society together.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Ritchie Robertson portrays it as a grand intellectual and political program, offering a "science" of society modeled on the powerful physical laws of Newton.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] "Social science" was seen as the instrument of human improvement.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] It would expose truth and expand human happiness.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The rights of women and non-White people were generally overlooked in Enlightenment philosophy, which is often explicitly Eurocentric.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Scientific racism first emerged at this time, bringing together traditional racism and new research methods.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] During the Enlightenment, concepts of monogenism and polygenism became popular, though they would only be systematized epistemologically during the 19th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Monogenism contends that all races have a single origin, while polygenism is the idea that each race has a separate origin.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Until the 18th century, the words "race" and "species" were interchangeable.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The classification of non-European peoples as sub-human and irrational served to justify European dominance.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] The term "Enlightenment" emerged in English in the latter part of the 19th century, with particular reference to French philosophy, as the equivalent of the French term *Lumières* (used first by Jean-Baptiste Dubos in 1733 and already well established by 1751).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] From Kant's 1784 essay "Beantwortung der Frage: Was ist Aufklärung?" ("Answering the Question: What is Enlightenment?"), the German term became *Aufklärung* (*aufklären* = to illuminate; *sich aufklären* = to clear up).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] However, scholars have never agreed on a definition of the Enlightenment or on its chronological or geographical extent.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Terms like *les Lumières* (French), *illuminism*o (Italian), *ilustración* (Spanish) and *Aufklärung* (German) referred to partly overlapping movements.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Enlightenment historiography began in the period itself, from what Enlightenment figures said about their work.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] A dominant element was the intellectual angle they took.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jean le Rond d'Alembert's *Preliminary Discourse* of *l'Encyclopédie* provides a history of the Enlightenment which comprises a chronological list of developments in the realm of knowledge—of which the *Encyclopédie* forms the pinnacle.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In 1783, Mendelssohn referred to Enlightenment as a process by which man was educated in the use of reason.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Bertrand Russell saw the Enlightenment as a phase in a progressive development which began in antiquity and that reason and challenges to the established order were constant ideals throughout that time.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Although many of these philosophical ideals were picked up by Catholics, Russell argues that by the 18th century the Enlightenment was the principal manifestation of the schism that began with Martin Luther.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Jonathan Israel rejects the attempts of postmodern and Marxian historians to understand the revolutionary ideas of the period purely as by-products of social and economic transformations.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] He instead focuses on the history of ideas in the period from 1650 to the end of the 18th century and claims that it was the ideas themselves that caused the change that eventually led to the revolutions of the latter half of the 18th century and the early 19th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] There is little consensus on the beginning of the Enlightenment, though several historians and philosophers argue that it was marked by Descartes' 1637 philosophy of *Cogito, ergo sum* ("I think, therefore I am"), which shifted the epistemological basis from external authority to internal certainty.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In France, many cited the publication of Newton's *Principia Mathematica* (1687), which built upon the work of earlier scientists and formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] French historians usually place the *Siècle des Lumières* ("Century of Enlightenments") between 1715 and 1789: from the beginning of the reign of Louis XV until the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Most scholars use the last years of the century, often choosing the French Revolution or the beginning of the Napoleonic Wars (1804) as a convenient point in time with which to date the end of the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In their 1947 book *Dialectic of Enlightenment,* Frankfurt School philosophers Max Horkheimer and Theodor W.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Extending Horkheimer and Adorno's argument, intellectual historian Jason Josephson Storm argues that any idea of the Enlightenment as a clearly defined period that is separate from the earlier Renaissance and later Romanticism or Counter-Enlightenment constitutes a myth.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Storm defends his categorization of the Enlightenment as "myth" by noting the regulative role ideas of a period of Enlightenment and disenchantment play in modern Western culture, such that belief in magic, spiritualism, and even religion appears somewhat taboo in intellectual strata.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] In the 1970s, study of the Enlightenment expanded to include the ways Enlightenment ideas spread to European colonies and how they interacted with indigenous cultures and how the Enlightenment took place in formerly unstudied areas such as Italy, Greece, the Balkans, Poland, Hungary, and Russia.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Intellectuals such as Robert Darnton and Jürgen Habermas have focused on the social conditions of the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas described the creation of the "bourgeois public sphere" in 18th-century Europe, containing the new venues and modes of communication allowing for rational exchange.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] Habermas said that the public sphere was bourgeois, egalitarian, rational, and independent from the state, making it the ideal venue for intellectuals to critically examine contemporary politics and society, away from the interference of established authority.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p02] While the public sphere is generally an integral component of the social study of the Enlightenment, other historians have questioned whether the public sphere had these characteristics.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This approach studies the process of changing sociabilities and cultural practices during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Elements of the public sphere included that it was egalitarian, that it discussed the domain of "common concern," and that argument was founded on reason.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Habermas uses the term "common concern" to describe those areas of political/social knowledge and discussion that were previously the exclusive territory of the state and religious authorities, now open to critical examination by the public sphere.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The values of this bourgeois public sphere included holding reason to be supreme, considering everything to be open to criticism (the public sphere is critical), and the opposition of secrecy of all sorts.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The creation of the public sphere has been associated with two long-term historical trends: the rise of the modern nation state and the rise of capitalism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The modern nation state in its consolidation of public power created by counterpoint a private realm of society independent of the state, which allowed for the public sphere.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Capitalism also increased society's autonomy and self-awareness, as well as an increasing need for the exchange of information.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the nascent public sphere expanded, it embraced a large variety of institutions, and the most commonly cited were coffee houses and cafés, salons and the literary public sphere, figuratively localized in the Republic of Letters.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the creation of the public sphere was helped by the aristocracy's move from the king's palace at Versailles to Paris in about 1720, since their rich spending stimulated the trade in luxuries and artistic creations, especially fine paintings.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The word "public" implies the highest level of inclusivity—the public sphere by definition should be open to all.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, this sphere was only public to relative degrees.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Cross-class influences occurred through noble and lower class participation in areas such as the coffeehouses and the Masonic lodges.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Because of the focus on reason over superstition, the Enlightenment cultivated the arts.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Emphasis on learning, art, and music became more widespread, especially with the growing middle class.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Areas of study such as literature, philosophy, science, and the fine arts increasingly explored subject matter to which the general public, in addition to the previously more segregated professionals and patrons, could relate.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As musicians depended more on public support, public concerts became increasingly popular and helped supplement performers' and composers' incomes.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The concerts also helped them to reach a wider audience.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Handel, for example, epitomized this with his highly public musical activities in London.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] He gained considerable fame there with performances of his operas and oratorios.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The music of Haydn and Mozart, with their Viennese Classical styles, are usually regarded as being the most in line with the Enlightenment ideals.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The desire to explore, record, and systematize knowledge had a meaningful impact on music publications.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rousseau's *Dictionnaire de musique* (published 1767 in Geneva and 1768 in Paris) was a leading text in the late 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This widely available dictionary gave short definitions of words like genius and taste and was clearly influenced by the Enlightenment movement.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Another text influenced by Enlightenment values was Charles Burney's *A General History of Music: From the Earliest Ages to the Present Period* (1776), which was a historical survey and an attempt to rationalize elements in music systematically over time.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Recently, musicologists have shown renewed interest in the ideas and consequences of the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the economy and the middle class expanded, there was an increasing number of amateur musicians.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One manifestation of this involved women, who became more involved with music on a social level.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Women were already engaged in professional roles as singers and increased their presence in the amateur performers' scene, especially with keyboard music.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music publishers began to print music that amateurs could understand and play.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The majority of the works that were published were for keyboard, voice and keyboard, and chamber ensemble.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After these initial genres were popularized, from the mid-century on, amateur groups sang choral music, which then became a new trend for publishers to capitalize on.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increasing study of the fine arts, as well as access to amateur-friendly published works, led to more people becoming interested in reading and discussing music.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Music magazines, reviews, and critical works which suited amateurs as well as connoisseurs began to surface.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *philosophes* spent a great deal of energy disseminating their ideas among educated men and women in cosmopolitan cities.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They used many venues, some of them quite new.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Republic of Letters was the sum of a number of Enlightenment ideals: an egalitarian realm governed by knowledge that could act across political boundaries and rival state power.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was a forum that supported "free public examination of questions regarding religion or legislation." Kant considered written communication essential to his conception of the public sphere; once everyone was a part of the "reading public," then society could be said to be enlightened.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The people who participated in the Republic of Letters, such as Diderot and Voltaire, are frequently known today as important Enlightenment figures.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While women were marginalized in the public culture of the Old Regime, the French Revolution destroyed the old cultural and economic restraints of patronage and corporatism (medieval guilds), opening French society to female participation, particularly in the literary sphere.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the established men of letters (*gens de lettres*) had fused with the elites (*les grands*) of French society by the mid-18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was Grub Street literature that was most read by the public during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] According to Darnton, more importantly the Grub Street hacks inherited the "revolutionary spirit" once displayed by the *philosophes* and paved the way for the French Revolution by desacralizing figures of political, moral, and religious authority in France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The increased consumption of reading materials of all sorts was one of the key features of the "social" Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, demand for reading material extended outside of the realm of the commercial and outside the realm of the upper and middle classes, as evidenced by the bibliothèque bleue.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Literacy rates are difficult to gauge, but in France the rates doubled over the course of the 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reflecting the decreasing influence of religion, the number of books about science and art published in Paris doubled from 1720 to 1780, while the number of books about religion dropped to just one-tenth of the total.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Reading underwent serious changes in the 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In particular, Rolf Engelsing has argued for the existence of a *reading revolution.* Until 1750, reading was done intensively: people tended to own a small number of books and read them repeatedly, often to small audience.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] After 1750, people began to read "extensively," finding as many books as they could, increasingly reading them alone.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is supported by increasing literacy rates, particularly among women.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The vast majority of the reading public could not afford to own a private library, and while most of the state-run "universal libraries" set up in the 17th and 18th centuries were open to the public, they were not the only sources of reading material.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On one end of the spectrum was the *bibliothèque bleue,* a collection of cheaply produced books published in Troyes, France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Intended for a largely rural and semi-literate audience these books included almanacs, retellings of medieval romances and condensed versions of popular novels, among other things.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] While some historians have argued against the Enlightenment's penetration into the lower classes, the *bibliothèque bleue* represents at least a desire to participate in Enlightenment sociability.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Moving up the classes, a variety of institutions offered readers access to material without needing to buy anything.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Libraries that lent out their material for a small price started to appear, and occasionally bookstores would offer a small lending library to their patrons.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffee houses commonly offered books, journals, and sometimes even popular novels to their customers.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Tatler* and *The Spectator,* two influential periodicals sold from 1709 to 1714, were closely associated with coffee house culture in London, being both read and produced in various establishments in the city.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is an example of the triple or even quadruple function of the coffee house: reading material was often obtained, read, discussed, and even produced on the premises.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It is difficult to determine what people actually read during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, examining the catalogs of private libraries gives an image skewed in favor of the classes wealthy enough to afford libraries and also ignores censored works unlikely to be publicly acknowledged.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For this reason, a study of publishing would be much more fruitful for discerning reading habits.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Across continental Europe, but in France especially, booksellers and publishers had to negotiate censorship laws of varying strictness.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie* narrowly escaped seizure and had to be saved by Malesherbes, the man in charge of the French censor.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, many publishing companies were conveniently located outside France so as to avoid overzealous French censors.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They would smuggle their merchandise across the border, where it would then be transported to clandestine booksellers or small-time peddlers.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The records of clandestine booksellers may give a better representation of what literate Frenchmen might have truly read, since their clandestine nature provided a less restrictive product choice.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In one case, political books were the most popular category, primarily libels and pamphlets.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Readers were more interested in sensationalist stories about criminals and political corruption than they were in political theory itself.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The second most popular category, "general works" (those books "that did not have a dominant motif and that contained something to offend almost everyone in authority"), demonstrated a high demand for generally low-brow subversive literature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, these works never became part of literary canon and are largely forgotten today as a result.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A healthy, legal publishing industry existed throughout Europe, although established publishers and book sellers occasionally ran afoul of the law.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the *Encyclopédie*, condemned by both the King and Clement XII, nevertheless found its way into print with the help of the aforementioned Malesherbes and creative use of French censorship law.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, many works were sold without running into any legal trouble at all.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Borrowing records from libraries in England, Germany, and North America indicate that more than 70% of books borrowed were novels.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Less than 1% of the books were of a religious nature, indicating the general trend of declining religiosity.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A genre that greatly rose in importance was that of scientific literature.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Natural history in particular became increasingly popular among the upper classes.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Works of natural history include René-Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur's *Histoire naturelle des insectes* and Jacques Gautier d'Agoty's *La Myologie complète, ou description de tous les muscles du corps humain* (1746).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Outside Ancien Régime France, natural history was an important part of medicine and industry, encompassing the fields of botany, zoology, meteorology, hydrology, and mineralogy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Students in Enlightenment universities and academies were taught these subjects to prepare them for careers as diverse as medicine and theology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As shown by Matthew Daniel Eddy, natural history in this context was a very middle class pursuit and operated as a fertile trading zone for the interdisciplinary exchange of diverse scientific ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The target audience of natural history was French upper class, evidenced more by the specific discourse of the genre than by the generally high prices of its works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Naturalists catered to upper class desire for erudition: many texts had an explicit instructive purpose.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, natural history was often a political affair.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In this way, natural history spread many of the scientific developments of the time but also provided a new source of legitimacy for the dominant class.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From this basis, naturalists could then develop their own social ideals based on their scientific works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first scientific and literary journals were established during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first journal, the Parisian *Journal des sçavans*, appeared in 1665.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, it was not until 1682 that periodicals began to be more widely produced.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French and Latin were the dominant languages of publication, but there was also a steady demand for material in German and Dutch.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] There was generally low demand for English publications on the continent, which was echoed by England's similar lack of desire for French works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Languages commanding less of an international market—such as Danish, Spanish, and Portuguese—found journal success more difficult, and a more international language was used instead.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] French slowly took over Latin's status as the *lingua franca* of learned circles.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This in turn gave precedence to the publishing industry in Holland, where the vast majority of these French language periodicals were produced.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Jonathan Israel called the journals the most influential cultural innovation of European intellectual culture.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They shifted the attention of the "cultivated public" away from established authorities to novelty and innovation, and instead promoted the Enlightened ideals of toleration and intellectual objectivity.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Being a source of knowledge derived from science and reason, they were an implicit critique of existing notions of universal truth monopolized by monarchies, parliaments, and religious authorities.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They also advanced Christian Enlightenment that upheld "the legitimacy of God-ordained authority"—the Bible—in which there had to be agreement between the biblical and natural theories.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although the existence of dictionaries and encyclopedias spanned into ancient times, the texts changed from defining words in a long running list to far more detailed discussions of those words in 18th-century encyclopedic dictionaries.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The works were part of an Enlightenment movement to systematize knowledge and provide education to a wider audience than the elite.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the 18th century progressed, the content of encyclopedias also changed according to readers' tastes.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Volumes tended to focus more strongly on secular affairs, particularly science and technology, rather than matters of theology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with secular matters, readers also favoured an alphabetical ordering scheme over cumbersome works arranged along thematic lines.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Encyclopedias and dictionaries also became more popular during the Enlightenment as the number of educated consumers who could afford such texts began to multiply.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the latter half of the 18th century, the number of dictionaries and encyclopedias published by decade increased from 63 between 1760 and 1769 to approximately 148 in the decade proceeding the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Along with growth in numbers, dictionaries and encyclopedias also grew in length, often having multiple print runs that sometimes included in supplemented editions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first technical dictionary was drafted by John Harris and entitled *Lexicon Technicum: Or, An Universal English Dictionary of Arts and Sciences.* Harris' book avoids theological and biographical entries and instead concentrates on science and technology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Published in 1704, the *Lexicon Technicum* was the first book to be written in English that took a methodical approach to describing mathematics and commercial arithmetic along with the physical sciences and navigation.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Other technical dictionaries followed Harris' model, including Ephraim Chambers' *Cyclopaedia* (1728), which included five editions and is a substantially larger work than Harris'.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The folio edition of the work even included foldout engravings.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Cyclopaedia* emphasized Newtonian theories, Lockean philosophy and contained thorough examinations of technologies, such as engraving, brewing, and dyeing.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In Germany, practical reference works intended for the uneducated majority became popular in the 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The *Marperger Curieuses Natur-, Kunst-, Berg-, Gewerk- und Handlungs-Lexicon* (1712) explained terms that usefully described the trades and scientific and commercial education.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] *Jablonksi Allgemeines Lexicon* (1721) was better known than the *Handlungs-Lexicon* and underscored technical subjects rather than scientific theory.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, over five columns of text were dedicated to wine while geometry and logic were allocated only twenty-two and seventeen lines, respectively.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first edition of the *Encyclopædia Britannica* (1771) was modelled along the same lines as the German lexicons.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the prime example of reference works that systematized scientific knowledge in the Enlightenment were universal encyclopedias rather than technical dictionaries.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was the goal of universal encyclopedias to record all human knowledge in a comprehensive reference work.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The most well-known of these works is Diderot and d'Alembert's *Encyclopédie, ou dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers.* The work, which began publication in 1751, was composed of 35 volumes and over 71,000 separate entries.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A great number of the entries were dedicated to describing the sciences and crafts in detail and provided intellectuals across Europe with a high-quality survey of human knowledge.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The massive work was arranged according to a "tree of knowledge." The tree reflected the marked division between the arts and sciences, which was largely a result of the rise of empiricism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Both areas of knowledge were united by philosophy, or the trunk of the tree of knowledge.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Enlightenment's desacrilization of religion was pronounced in the tree's design, particularly where theology accounted for a peripheral branch, with black magic as a close neighbour.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] As the *Encyclopédie* gained popularity, it was published in quarto and octavo editions after 1777.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The quarto and octavo editions were much less expensive than previous editions, making the *Encyclopédie* more accessible to the non-elite.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Robert Darnton estimates that there were approximately 25,000 copies of the *Encyclopédie* in circulation throughout France and Europe before the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The extensive yet affordable encyclopedia came to represent the transmission of Enlightenment and scientific education to an expanding audience.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most important developments that the Enlightenment era brought to the discipline of science was its popularization.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] An increasingly literate population seeking knowledge and education in both the arts and the sciences drove the expansion of print culture and the dissemination of scientific learning.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The new literate population was precipitated by a high rise in the availability of food; this enabled many people to rise out of poverty, and instead of paying more for food, they had money for education.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More formal works included explanations of scientific theories for individuals lacking the educational background to comprehend the original scientific text.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Newton's celebrated *Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica* was published in Latin and remained inaccessible to readers without education in the classics until Enlightenment writers began to translate and analyze the text in the vernacular.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first significant work that expressed scientific theory and knowledge expressly for the laity, in the vernacular and with the entertainment of readers in mind, was Bernard de Fontenelle's *Conversations on the Plurality of Worlds* (1686).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The book was produced specifically for women with an interest in scientific writing and inspired a variety of similar works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These popular works were written in a discursive style, which was laid out much more clearly for the reader than the complicated articles, treatises, and books published by the academies and scientists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Writing for a growing female audience, Francesco Algarotti published *Il Newtonianism per le dame*, which was a tremendously popular work and was translated from Italian into English by Elizabeth Carter.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] A similar introduction to Newtonianism for women was produced by Henry Pemberton.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] His *A View of Sir Isaac Newton's Philosophy* was published by subscription.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Extant records of subscribers show that women from a wide range of social standings purchased the book, indicating the growing number of scientifically inclined female readers among the middling class.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, women also began producing popular scientific works.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Sarah Trimmer wrote a successful natural history textbook for children titled *The Easy Introduction to the Knowledge of Nature* (1782), which was published for many years in eleven editions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Most work on the Enlightenment emphasizes the ideals discussed by intellectuals, rather than the actual state of education at the time.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leading educational theorists like England's John Locke and Switzerland's Jean Jacques Rousseau both emphasized the importance of shaping young minds early.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] By the late Enlightenment, there was a rising demand for a more universal approach to education, particularly after the American Revolution and the French Revolution.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The predominant educational psychology from the 1750s onward, especially in northern European countries, was associationism: the notion that the mind associates or dissociates ideas through repeated routines.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Children were taught to memorize facts through oral and graphic methods that originated during the Renaissance.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Many of the leading universities associated with Enlightenment progressive principles were located in northern Europe, with the most renowned being the universities of Leiden, Göttingen, Halle, Montpellier, Uppsala, and Edinburgh.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These universities, especially Edinburgh, produced professors whose ideas had a significant impact on Britain's North American colonies and later the American Republic.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Within the natural sciences, Edinburgh's medical school also led the way in chemistry, anatomy, and pharmacology.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In other parts of Europe, the universities and schools of France and most of Europe were bastions of traditionalism and were not hospitable to the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In France, the major exception was the medical university at Montpellier.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The history of Academies in France during the Enlightenment begins with the Academy of Science, founded in 1666 in Paris.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was closely tied to the French state, acting as an extension of a government seriously lacking in scientists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It helped promote and organize new disciplines and it trained new scientists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It also contributed to the enhancement of scientists' social status, considering them to be the "most useful of all citizens." Academies demonstrate the rising interest in science along with its increasing secularization, as evidenced by the small number of clerics who were members (13%).
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of the French academies in the public sphere cannot be attributed to their membership, as although the majority of their members were bourgeois, the exclusive institution was only open to elite Parisian scholars.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They perceived themselves as "interpreters of the sciences for the people." For example, it was with this in mind that academicians took it upon themselves to disprove the popular pseudo-science of mesmerism.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The strongest contribution of the French Academies to the public sphere comes from the *concours académiques* (roughly translated as "academic contests") they sponsored throughout France.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These academic contests were perhaps the most public of any institution during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The practice of contests dated back to the Middle Ages and was revived in the mid-17th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The subject matter had previously been generally religious and/or monarchical, featuring essays, poetry, and painting.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] More importantly, the contests were open to all, and the enforced anonymity of each submission guaranteed that neither gender nor social rank would determine the judging.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, although the "vast majority" of participants belonged to the wealthier strata of society ("the liberal arts, the clergy, the judiciary and the medical profession"), there were some cases of the popular classes submitting essays and even winning.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similarly, a significant number of women participated—and won—the competitions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Of a total of 2,300 prize competitions offered in France, women won 49—perhaps a small number by modern standards but very significant in an age in which very few women had any academic training.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Indeed, the majority of the winning entries were for poetry competitions, a genre commonly stressed in women's education.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In England, the Royal Society of London played a significant role in the public sphere and the spread of Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was founded by a group of independent scientists and given a royal charter in 1662.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The society played a large role in spreading Robert Boyle's experimental philosophy around Europe and acted as a clearinghouse for intellectual correspondence and exchange.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Boyle was "a founder of the experimental world in which scientists now live and operate" and his method based knowledge on experimentation, which had to be witnessed to provide proper empirical legitimacy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This is where the Royal Society came into play: witnessing had to be a "collective act" and the Royal Society's assembly rooms were ideal locations for relatively public demonstrations.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Salons were places where *philosophes* were reunited and discussed old, actual, or new ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This led to salons being the birthplace of intellectual and enlightened ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were especially important to the spread of knowledge during the Enlightenment because they created a unique environment in which people from many different walks of life gathered and shared ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They were frequently criticized by nobles who feared the possibility of an environment in which class and its accompanying titles and privileges were disregarded.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Such an environment was especially intimidating to monarchs who derived much of their power from the disparity between classes of people.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] If the different classes joined together under the influence of Enlightenment thinking, they might recognize the all-encompassing oppression and abuses of their monarchs and because of the numbers of their members might be able to successfully revolt.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Monarchs also resented the idea of their subjects convening as one to discuss political matters, especially matters of foreign affairs.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Rulers thought political affairs were their business only, a result of their divine right to rule.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeeshops became homes away from home for many who sought to engage in discourse with their neighbors and discuss intriguing and thought-provoking matters, from philosophy to politics.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses were essential to the Enlightenment, for they were centers of free-thinking and self-discovery.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Although many coffeehouse patrons were scholars, many were not.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Coffeehouses attracted a diverse set of people, including the educated wealthy and bourgeois as well as the lower classes.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Patrons, being doctors, lawyers, merchants, represented almost all classes, so the coffeeshop environment sparked fear in those who wanted to preserve class distinction.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One of the most popular critiques of the coffeehouse said that it "allowed promiscuous association among people from different rungs of the social ladder, from the artisan to the aristocrat" and was therefore compared to Noah's Ark, receiving all types of animals, clean and unclean.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This unique culture served as a catalyst for journalism, when Joseph Addison and Richard Steele recognized its potential as an audience.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Together, Steele and Addison published *The Spectator (1711)*, a daily publication which aimed, through fictional narrator Mr.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Spectator, to both entertain and provoke discussion on serious philosophical matters.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The first English coffeehouse opened in Oxford in 1650.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Brian Cowan said that Oxford coffeehouses developed into "penny universities," offering a locus of learning that was less formal than at structured institutions.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These penny universities occupied a significant position in Oxford academic life, as they were frequented by those consequently referred to as the *virtuosi,* who conducted their research on some of the premises.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was established in Paris in 1686, and by the 1720s there were around 400 cafés in the city.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope in particular became a center of Enlightenment, welcoming such celebrities as Voltaire and Rousseau.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Café Procope was where Diderot and D'Alembert decided to create the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The cafés were one of the various "nerve centers" for *bruits publics,* public noise or rumour.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] These *bruits* were allegedly a much better source of information than were the actual newspapers available at the time.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies are an example of the public sphere during the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In the late 1770s, popular debating societies began to move into more "genteel" rooms, a change which helped establish a new standard of sociability.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The backdrop to these developments was "an explosion of interest in the theory and practice of public elocution." The debating societies were commercial enterprises that responded to this demand, sometimes very successfully.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Some societies welcomed from 800 to 1,200 spectators per night.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The debating societies discussed an extremely wide range of topics.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In addition to debates on religion, societies discussed issues such as politics and the role of women.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] However, the critical subject matter of these debates did not necessarily translate into opposition to the government; the results of the debate quite frequently upheld the *status quo*.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] From a historical standpoint, one of the most important features of the debating society was their openness to the public, as women attended and even participated in almost every debating society, which were likewise open to all classes providing they could pay the entrance fee.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Once inside, spectators were able to participate in a largely egalitarian form of sociability that helped spread Enlightenment ideas.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historians have debated the extent to which the secret network of Freemasonry was a main factor in the Enlightenment.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Leaders of the Enlightenment included Freemasons such as Diderot, Montesquieu, Voltaire, Lessing, Pope, Horace Walpole, Robert Walpole, Mozart, Goethe, Frederick the Great, Benjamin Franklin and George Washington.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Norman Davies said Freemasonry was a powerful force on behalf of liberalism in Europe from about 1700 to the twentieth century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It expanded during the Enlightenment, reaching practically every country in Europe.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] It was especially attractive to powerful aristocrats and politicians as well as intellectuals, artists, and political activists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] During the Enlightenment, Freemasons comprised an international network of like-minded men, often meeting in secret in ritualistic programs at their lodges.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They promoted the ideals of the Enlightenment and helped diffuse these values across Britain, France, and other places.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry as a systematic creed with its own myths, values, and rituals originated in Scotland c.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] 1600 and spread to England and then across the Continent in the 18th century.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Freemasonry was particularly prevalent in France—by 1789, there were perhaps as many as 100,000 French Masons, making Freemasonry the most popular of all Enlightenment associations.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Freemasons displayed a passion for secrecy and created new degrees and ceremonies.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Similar societies, partially imitating Freemasonry, emerged in France, Germany, Sweden, and Russia.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] One example was the Illuminati, founded in Bavaria in 1776, which was copied after the Freemasons, but was never part of the movement.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The name itself translates to "enlightened," chosen to reflect their original intent to promote the values of the movement.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The Illuminati was an overtly political group, which most Masonic lodges decidedly were not.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Masonic lodges created a private model for public affairs.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] They "reconstituted the polity and established a constitutional form of self-government, complete with constitutions and laws, elections, and representatives." In other words, the micro-society set up within the lodges constituted a normative model for society as a whole.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] This was especially true on the continent: when the first lodges began to appear in the 1730s, their embodiment of British values was often seen as threatening by state authorities.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, the Parisian lodge that met in the mid 1720s was composed of English Jacobite exiles.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Furthermore, freemasons across Europe explicitly linked themselves to the Enlightenment as a whole.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] For example, in French lodges the line "As the means to be enlightened I search for the enlightened" was a part of their initiation rites.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] British lodges assigned themselves the duty to "initiate the unenlightened." This did not necessarily link lodges to the irreligious, but neither did this exclude them from the occasional heresy.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] In fact, many lodges praised the Grand Architect, the masonic terminology for the deistic divine being who created a scientifically ordered universe.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Diderot discusses the link between Freemason ideals and the enlightenment in D'Alembert's Dream, exploring masonry as a way of spreading enlightenment beliefs.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Historian Margaret Jacob stresses the importance of the Masons in indirectly inspiring enlightened political thought.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] On the negative side, Daniel Roche contests claims that Masonry promoted egalitarianism and he argues the lodges only attracted men of similar social backgrounds.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The presence of noble women in the French "lodges of adoption" that formed in the 1780s was largely due to the close ties shared between these lodges and aristocratic society.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] The major opponent of Freemasonry was the Catholic Church so in countries with a large Catholic element, such as France, Italy, Spain, and Mexico, much of the ferocity of the political battles involve the confrontation between what Davies calls the reactionary Church and enlightened Freemasonry.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] Even in France, Masons did not act as a group.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] American historians, while noting that Benjamin Franklin and George Washington were indeed active Masons, have downplayed the importance of Freemasonry in causing the American Revolution because the Masonic order was non-political and included both Patriots and their enemy the Loyalists.
[src:bevanism/age-of-enlightenment-p03] At the same time, the classical art of Greece and Rome became interesting to people again, since archaeological teams discovered Pompeii and Herculaneum.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] After the February Revolution of 1917, he joined the newly formed provisional government, first as Minister of Justice, then as Minister of War, and after July as the government's second Minister-Chairman.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He was the leader of the social-democratic Trudovik faction of the Socialist Revolutionary Party.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was also a vice-chairman of the Petrograd Soviet, a position that held a sizable amount of power.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became the prime minister of the Provisional Government, and his tenure was consumed with World War I.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Despite mass opposition to the war, Kerensky chose to continue Russia's participation.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His government cracked down on anti-war sentiment and dissent in 1917, which made his administration even more unpopular.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky remained in power until the October Revolution.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] This revolution saw the Bolsheviks create a government led by them in a coalition with the Left Socialist-Revolutionaries, to replace Kerensky's government.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky fled Russia and lived the remainder of his life in exile, mostly in Paris and New York City.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He also worked for the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, California.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He died in New York on 11 June 1970, at the age of 89.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Both the local Russian and Serbian Orthodox churches refused his body due to his Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolshevik seizure of power.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Eventually, his body was flown to London and buried in the non-sectarian Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Alexander Kerensky was born in Simbirsk (now Ulyanovsk) on the Volga river on 4 May 1881 and was the eldest son in the family.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His father, Fyodor Mikhailovich Kerensky, was a teacher and director of the local gymnasium, and was later promoted to be an inspector of public schools.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His paternal grandfather Mikhail Ivanovich served as a priest in the village of Kerenka in the Gorodishchensky district of the Penza Governorate from 1830.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The surname Kerensky comes from the name of this village.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His maternal grandfather was head of the Topographical Bureau of the Kazan Military District.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His mother, Nadezhda Aleksandrovna (née Adler), was the granddaughter of a former serf who had managed to purchase his freedom before serfdom was abolished in 1861.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He subsequently embarked upon a mercantile career, in which he prospered.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] This allowed him to move his business to Moscow, where he continued his success and became a wealthy Moscow merchant.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Members of the Kerensky and Ulyanov families were friends; Kerensky's father was the teacher of Vladimir Ulyanov (Lenin), and had even secured him acceptance into the University of Kazan.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In 1889, when Kerensky was eight, the family moved to Tashkent, where his father had been appointed the superintendent of public schools.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky graduated with honours in 1899.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Petersburg University, where he studied history and philology.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He earned his law degree in 1904 and married Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya, the daughter of a Russian general, the same year.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky joined the Narodnik movement and worked as a legal counsel to victims of the Revolution of 1905.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] At the end of 1904, he was jailed on suspicion of belonging to a militant group.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Afterwards, he gained a reputation for his work as a defence lawyer in a number of political trials of revolutionaries.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In 1912, Kerensky became widely known when he visited the goldfields at the Lena River and published material about the Lena massacre.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In fact, the Socialist Revolutionary Party bought Kerensky a house, as he otherwise would not be eligible for election to the Duma, according to the Russian property laws.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 8. stop the harassment of legal trade union organizations.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In August, he became a significant member of the Progressive Bloc, which included several socialist parties, Mensheviks, and Liberals – but not Bolsheviks.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was an active member of the irregular Freemasonic lodge the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples, which derived from the Grand Orient of France.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was Secretary-General of the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples and stood down following his ascent to the government in July 1917.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He was succeeded by a Menshevik, Alexander Halpern.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] According to Kerensky, Rasputin had terrorised the empress by threatening to return to his native village.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Members of the nobility murdered Rasputin in December 1916, and he was buried near the imperial residence in Tsarskoye Selo.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Shortly after the February Revolution of 1917, Kerensky ordered soldiers to re-bury the corpse at an unmarked spot in the countryside.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] However, the truck broke down or was forced to stop because of the snow on Lesnoe Road outside of St.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] It is likely the corpse was incinerated (between 3 and 7 in the morning) in the cauldrons of the nearby boiler shop of the Saint Petersburg State Polytechnical University, including the coffin, without leaving a single trace.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] When the February Revolution broke out in 1917, Kerensky – together with Pavel Milyukov – was one of its most prominent leaders.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] As one of the Duma's most well-known speakers against the monarchy and as a lawyer and defender of many revolutionaries, Kerensky became a member of the Provisional Committee of the State Duma and was elected vice-chairman of the newly formed Petrograd Soviet.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] These two bodies, the Duma and the Petrograd Soviet, or – rather – their respective executive committees, soon became each other's antagonists on most matters except regarding the end of the tsar's autocracy.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The Petrograd Soviet grew to include 3000 to 4000 members, and their meetings could drown into a blur of lengthy speeches.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 28 February] 1917 the executive committee of the Petrograd Soviet, or Ispolkom, formed a self-appointed committee, with (eventually) three members from each of the parties represented in the Soviet.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became one of the members representing the Socialist Revolutionary Party (the SRs).
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 1 March] 1917, without any consultation with the government, the Ispolkom of the Soviet issued the infamous Order No.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 1, intended only for the 160,000-strong Petrograd garrison, but soon interpreted as applicable to all soldiers at the front.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The order stipulated that all military units should form committees like the Petrograd Soviet.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] This led to confusion and "stripping of officers' authority"; further, "Order No.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 3" stipulated that the military was subordinate to Ispolkom in the political hierarchy.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The ideas came from a group of socialists and aimed to limit the officers' power to military affairs.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The socialist intellectuals believed the officers to be the most likely counterrevolutionary elements.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's role in these orders is unclear, but he participated in the decisions.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] But just as before the revolution he had defended many who disliked the tsar, he now saved the lives of many of the tsar's civil servants about to be lynched by mobs.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Additionally, the Duma formed an executive committee which eventually became the Russian Provisional Government.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] As there was little trust between Ispolkom and this government (and as he was about to accept the office of Attorney General in the Provisional Government), Kerensky gave a most passionate speech, not just to the Ispolkom, but to the entire Petrograd Soviet.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He then swore, as minister, never to violate democratic values, and ended his speech with the words "I cannot live without the people.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In the moment you begin to doubt me, then kill me." The huge majority (workers and soldiers) gave him great applause, and Kerensky now became the first and *the only one* who participated in both the Provisional Government and the Ispolkom.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] As a link between Ispolkom and the Provisional Government, Kerensky stood to benefit from this position.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] After the first government crisis over Milyukov's secret note re-committing Russia to its original war-aims on 2–4 May, Kerensky became the Minister of War and the dominant figure in the newly formed socialist-liberal coalition government.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] On 10 May (Julian calendar), Kerensky started for the front and visited one division after another, urging the men to do their duty.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His speeches were impressive and convincing for the moment, but had little lasting effect.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Under Allied pressure to continue the war, he launched what became known as the Kerensky Offensive against the Austro-Hungarian/German South Army on 1 July [O.S.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] At first successful, the offensive soon met strong resistance and the Central Powers riposted with a strong counter-attack.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army retreated and suffered heavy losses, and it became clear from many incidents of desertion, sabotage, and mutiny that the army was no longer willing to attack.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Many officers scornfully referred to commander-in-chief Kerensky as the "persuader-in-chief".
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] On 2 July 1917 the Provisional Government's first coalition collapsed over the question of Ukraine's autonomy.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Following the July Days unrest in Petrograd (3–7 July [16–20 July, N.S.] 1917) and the official suppression of the Bolsheviks, Kerensky succeeded Lvov as Russia's prime minister on 21 July [O.S.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Following the Kornilov Affair, an attempted military coup d'état at the end of August, and the resignation of the other ministers, he appointed himself Supreme Commander-in-Chief, as well.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He formed a five-member Directory, which consisted of himself, Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Tereshchenko, Minister of War General Aleksandr Verkhovsky, Minister of the Navy Admiral Dmitry Verderevsky and Minister of Posts and Telegraphs Aleksei Nikitin.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He retained his post in the final coalition government in October 1917 until the Bolsheviks overthrew it on 7 November [O.S.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky faced a major challenge: three years of participation in World War had exhausted Russia, while the provisional government offered little motivation for a victory outside of continuing Russia's obligations towards its allies.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Russia's continued involvement in the war was not popular among the lower and middle classes, and especially not popular among the soldiers.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] They had all believed that Russia would stop fighting when the Provisional Government took power, and subsequently felt deceived.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Lenin and his Bolshevik party were promising "peace, land, and bread" under a communist system.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army, war-weary, ill-equipped, dispirited and ill-disciplined, was disintegrating, with soldiers deserting in large numbers.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] By autumn 1917, an estimated two million men had unofficially left the army.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The dilemma of whether to withdraw was a great one, and Kerensky's inconsistent and impractical policies further destabilised the army and the country at large.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Kerensky adopted a policy that isolated the right-wing conservatives and nationalists, both democratic and monarchist-oriented.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His philosophy of "no enemies to the left" greatly empowered the Bolsheviks and gave them a free hand, allowing them to take over the military arm or "voyenka" (Russian: Военка) of the Petrograd and Moscow Soviets.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] During the Kornilov Affair, Kerensky had distributed arms to the Petrograd workers, and by November most of these armed workers had gone over to the Bolsheviks.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] 25–26 October] 1917, the Bolsheviks launched the second Russian revolution of the year.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's government in Petrograd had almost no support in the city.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The Bolsheviks overthrew the government rapidly by seizing governmental buildings and the Winter Palace.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky escaped the Bolsheviks and fled to Pskov, where he rallied some loyal troops for an attempt to re-take the city.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His troops managed to capture Tsarskoye Selo but were beaten the next day at Pulkovo.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky narrowly escaped, and he spent the next few weeks in hiding before fleeing the country, eventually arriving in France.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] During the Russian Civil War, he supported neither side, as he opposed both the Bolshevik regime and the White Movement.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Meanwhile, viewed by Woodrow Wilson as the spokesman for Russian democracy, he strongly influenced Wilson on Russian matters.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was married to Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya and they had two sons, Oleg (1905–1984) and Gleb (1907–1990), who both went on to become engineers.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's grandson (also named Oleg), according to the Internet Movie Database, played his grandfather's role in the 1981 film *Reds*.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky and Olga were divorced in 1939 soon after he settled in Paris, and in the same year, while visiting the United States, he met and secretly married Lydia Ellen "Nell" Tritton (1899–1946), the Australian former journalist who had become his press secretary and translator.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The marriage took place in Martins Creek, Pennsylvania.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] When Germany invaded France in 1940, they emigrated to the United States.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] During the Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union, Kerensky expressed his willingness to support the Russian people's defense against Hitler, despite his long-standing opposition to the Soviet regime.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] In a published article, he criticized both Lenin and Stalin but stated that the survival of Russia as a nation took precedence over political differences.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] When his wife Nell became terminally ill in 1945, Kerensky travelled with her to Brisbane, Australia, and lived there with her family.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] She suffered a stroke in February 1946, and he remained there until her death on 10 April 1946.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky then returned to the United States, where he spent the rest of his life.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He wrote and broadcast extensively on Russian politics and history.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] His last public lecture was delivered at Kalamazoo College in Kalamazoo, Michigan, in October 1967.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky died of arteriosclerotic heart disease at St.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Luke's Hospital in New York City on 11 June 1970 at the age of 89, after being initially admitted for injuries sustained from a fall.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] He was one of the last surviving major participants in the turbulent events of 1917.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] The local Russian Orthodox Churches in New York City refused to grant Kerensky burial rites because of his association with Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolsheviks' seizure of power.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] A Serbian Orthodox Church also refused burial rites.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's body was flown to London, where his two sons resided; he was buried at the non-denominational Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:bevanism/alexander-kerensky] Papers of the Kerensky family are held at the Cadbury Research Library, University of Birmingham.
[src:bevanism/allendism] Allende's doctrine spoke of structurally reforming the country while at the same time trying to reach agreements with the Christian Democratic Party, the Confederation of Democracy, and the business sectors so as not to increase the internal and social tension that the country was experiencing.
[src:bevanism/allendism] The Communist Party, which favored these measures, spoke of "moving forward by consolidating".
[src:bevanism/allendism] During the coup, Pinochet ordered the immediate assassination of Carlos Altamirano, considering him a possible factor in armed resistance.
[src:bevanism/allendism] After the so-called “socialist renewal”, in which the exiles of the UP in Europe embraced and internalized the institutional framework and social democracy as ideological bases, Allendism adopted a more institutional and conciliatory character concerning the reforms raised by the same current.
[src:bevanism/allendism] Currently, experts define Allendism as a feeling of nostalgia for the Popular Unity period, without necessarily wanting to restore or retry the reforms made during that time.
[src:bevanism/allendism] After the Chilean transition to democracy, Allendism as a political ideology was welcomed by different left-wing political parties.
[src:bevanism/allendism] On December 9, 1991, the leftist political coalition *Movimiento de Izquierda Democrática Allendista* was formed.
[src:bevanism/allendism] It comprised the Communist Party, the Communist Party (Proletarian Action), MAPU, the Revolutionary Left Movement, and the Christian Left.
[src:bevanism/allendism] It was directed by Pedro Vuskovic, former socialist militant and Minister of Economy during the government of Allende, and also included other left-wing personalities among its main figures, such as priest Rafael Maroto and deputy Mario Palestro.
[src:bevanism/allendism] It participated in the 1992 municipal elections, achieving the election of 35 councilors and the appointment of Jorge Soria as mayor of the commune of Iquique.
[src:bevanism/allendism] In the 1993 presidential election, it supported the candidacy of priest Eugenio Pizarro and presented candidates for the National Congress in the parliamentary elections of that same year.
[src:bevanism/allendism] In the latter, it participated under the Left Democratic Alternative, officially registered with the Electoral Service on July 14.
[src:bevanism/allendism] The coalition formally dissolved on May 10, 1993.
[src:bevanism/allendism] On September 28, 2019, Jorge Arrate and Ernesto Águila founded the political party Socialist Platform.
[src:bevanism/allendism] In its beginnings, it was a member of Apruebo Dignidad, and since February 2023, it has been from the Broad Front.
[src:bevanism/allendism] The *Movimiento del Socialismo Allendista* emerged in 2021.
[src:bevanism/allendism] Its main leader is Esteban Silva Cuadra, who left the Socialist Party.
[src:bevanism/allendism] It was also a member of the *Allendistas por Jadue* commando, whose objective was to "ensure the victory" of the communist politician Daniel Jadue in the presidential primaries on July 18, and rescue Allende's legacy.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] He is a noted historian on the British Labour Party and Communist Party particularly in the era of the Communist International, having been one of the few foreign, non-party historians to have had access to archives in Moscow following the fall of the Soviet Union.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] January 2009 saw the publication of Thorpe's new work titled *Parties at War*, which examined all the major parties in Britain during the Second World War.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] The subject of the book has been the topic of his taught undergraduate module of the same name at the University of Exeter and is the product of over five years research.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] What Thorpe has done is examine more than 250 collections of regional and constituency records drawn from the Labour, Conservative and Liberal parties, and examined what occurred in the wartime period of political truce.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] Currently Professor Thorpe is working on the biography of Labour leader and Nobel prize winner Arthur Henderson.
[src:bevanism/andrew-thorpe] In September 2019 it was announced that Professor Thorpe will become the Executive Dean of the Faculty of Arts, Humanities and Cultures at the University of Leeds as well as becoming Professor of Modern History from 1 January 2020.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] Bevanism was influenced by Marxism; Bevan's biographer and later Leader of the Labour Party Michael Foot said that Bevan's "belief in the class conflict stayed unshaken", while acknowledging that Bevan was not a traditional Marxist.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] Despite declaring inspiration from Karl Marx, Bevan did not visibly support insurrectionist concepts of proletarian revolution, arguing that revolution depended on the circumstances, or the typical organisational model of many Communist parties.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] According to Ed Balls, Bevan and his supporters instead preferred a strident but pluralist conception of democratic socialism, tempered by pragmatic sensibilities and practical application.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] The Bevanite Group of MPs, of which there were about three dozen, coalesced following Bevan's resignation from the Cabinet in 1951 when the health service started charging for previously free services such as spectacles in order to help pay for Britain's involvement in the Korean War.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] Bevanites Harold Wilson and John Freeman resigned with Bevan himself.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] The group in Parliament drew heavily from the previous "Keep Left" group, which had previously dissented from the pro-American foreign policy of the 1945–1951 Labour government favoured by Clement Attlee, his Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin and Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] According to Crossman in December 1951 the group was not organised, and Bevan could not be persuaded to have any consistent or coherent strategy, but they did have a group who met regularly and liked each other and came to represent "real Socialism" to a large number of Party members.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] *Picture Post* called them the "Bevanly Host" in April 1952.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] Bevanites organised in Constituency Labour Parties across Britain, and set up local discussion groups known as "Brains Trusts", also a legacy of the "Keep Left" group.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] Brains Trusts organised in support of the newspaper favoured by Bevanites, *Tribune* magazine, allocating left-wing MPs and campaigners to form speaking panels around the country.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] *Tribune* itself provided an important print voice for Bevanite politicians and was in wide circulation.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] The Bevanite movement emerged from the earlier "Keep Left" group, which had formed in 1947 around the New Statesman journal and published pamphlets critiquing the Labour government's policies.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] The Keep Left group had attempted through discussion and pamphlets to produce practical proposals informed by socialist values, and their concerns about government economic and international policies showed affinities with later Bevanite positions.
[src:bevanism/bevanism] The Bevanites represented what they considered to be "real Socialism" and maintained strong support among constituency Labour parties, though the Gaitskellites typically won most of the battles inside Parliament, while Bevanism was stronger among local Labour activists.
